docs.abstract: After a tumultuous year, classrooms are talking about the murder of George Floyd.
docs.snippet: After a tumultuous year, classrooms are talking about the murder of George Floyd.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Wednesday, many teachers will have a big topic to discuss with their students: the news that a jury convicted Derek Chauvin of murder for the killing of George Floyd. We reached out to some of the educators who have been in touch with this newsletter to see how they’ll handle it.

headline.main: Teachers Address Derek Chauvin’s Guilty Verdict

docs.abstract: Business owners in Brooklyn Center, a suburb of Minneapolis, spent Monday repairing damaged property after a night of unrest. Protesters clashed with the police on Sunday, after an officer fatally shot a 20-year-old Black driver during a traffic stop. The shooting occurred not far from the courthouse where Derek Chauvin is on trial for the death of George Floyd.

docs.abstract: The trial of Derek Chauvin in the death of George Floyd is being livestreamed from Minneapolis.
docs.snippet: The trial of Derek Chauvin in the death of George Floyd is being livestreamed from Minneapolis.
docs.lead_paragraph: The trial of Derek Chauvin in the death of George Floyd is unusual for many reasons: It is being livestreamed from Minneapolis, attendance is severely limited because of the coronavirus and the public’s interest in the case may make this one of the highest-profile trials in recent memory.

headline.main: Here’s how to watch the closing arguments in the Derek Chauvin trial.

docs.abstract: It’s report card time for the Biden administration. Have the president’s actions met your expectations?
docs.snippet: It’s report card time for the Biden administration. Have the president’s actions met your expectations?
docs.lead_paragraph: When President Biden took office in January, we asked students what the new administration’s priorities should be. We heard from teenagers who wanted Mr. Biden to distribute coronavirus vaccines, support veterans, address police brutality, curb climate change and prioritize unity and bipartisanship.

headline.main: What Grade Would You Give President Biden on His First 100 Days?

docs.abstract: Relatives of George Floyd prayed outside the courthouse with the Rev. Al Sharpton on Tuesday, asking God for “justice” from the jury and for strength to continue closely watching the trial taking place on the 18th floor of the building behind them.

docs.abstract: After the deaths of Breonna Taylor and George Floyd and other instances of violence against Black people, many athletes engaged in activist efforts last year.
docs.snippet: After the deaths of Breonna Taylor and George Floyd and other instances of violence against Black people, many athletes engaged in activist efforts last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: The reverberations throughout sports came swiftly after a jury in Minnesota convicted Derek Chauvin on Tuesday of murdering George Floyd, as athletes, teams and leagues weighed in on the verdict in a case that had reignited fierce debate about racism and policing in the United States.

headline.main: Sports World Reacts to Chauvin Verdict

docs.abstract: Lt. Richard Zimmerman, who leads the homicide unit, said the police are supposed to quickly move people out of the prone position.
docs.snippet: Lt. Richard Zimmerman, who leads the homicide unit, said the police are supposed to quickly move people out of the prone position.
docs.lead_paragraph: The longest-serving police officer in the Minneapolis Police Department said on Friday that Derek Chauvin had violated department policy by kneeling on George Floyd’s neck for more than nine minutes as he lay handcuffed on his stomach.

headline.main: ‘Totally unnecessary’: the longest-serving Minneapolis Police officer says Chauvin violated police policy.

docs.abstract: Dr. Daniel Isenschmid said that intoxicated driving suspects who used fentanyl often had higher levels of the drug in their blood than Mr. Floyd did.
docs.snippet: Dr. Daniel Isenschmid said that intoxicated driving suspects who used fentanyl often had higher levels of the drug in their blood than Mr. Floyd did.
docs.lead_paragraph: A forensic toxicologist at the laboratory that tested George Floyd’s blood said it was common for intoxicated driving suspects who used fentanyl to have higher levels of the drug in their systems than Mr. Floyd did when he died. Prosecutors hoped his testimony would strike a blow to the argument by Derek Chauvin’s lawyer that Mr. Floyd’s death may have been an overdose.

headline.main: A toxicologist’s testimony challenged claims by Derek Chauvin’s lawyer that George Floyd overdosed on fentanyl.

byline.original: By Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs and Marie Fazio

docs.lead_paragraph: The third week of testimony in the trial of the former officer Derek Chauvin began on Monday with prosecutors continuing to call witnesses they think will bolster their argument that Mr. Chauvin caused George Floyd’s death by pinning him to the ground for more than nine minutes.
